---
// src/pages/index.astro
import CONFIG from '../config/conf'
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
---

<BaseLayout
    headTitle="YINI Config Format ‚Äî Simple, Structured Configuration Language"
    headDescription="Official site for the YINI configuration format ‚Äî an INI-inspired, human-friendly configuration language with nesting, arrays, and a formal specification."
>
    <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 py-2 text-center">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight md:text-5xl">
            {CONFIG.text.headline}
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-base text-gray-600 md:text-lg">
            {CONFIG.text.elevatorPitch}
        </p>

        <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
            <a href="/get-started" class="btn btn-primary"> Get Started </a>

            <!-- !!Temp disabled
            <a href="/playground" class="btn btn-outline"> Open Playground </a>
            -->

            <a href="/yini-tutorial" class="inline-block underline">
                Quick tutorial
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="why-yini pb-4">
        <h2>üí° Why YINI?</h2>
        INI is simple and familiar, but it lacks structure for complex data.<br
        />
        YAML offers rich features, though it can be harder to read and lint consistently.<br
        />
        JSON is precise and universal, but less concise for human editing.<br />
        YINI aims to balance these aspects ‚Äî keeping readability while providing
        clear nesting and predictable behavior.
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Familiar</strong> ‚Äî learn it in minutes if you know INI
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Structured</strong> ‚Äî sections, arrays, objects, clear nesting
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Predictable</strong> ‚Äî fewer gotchas; strict/lenient modes
                available
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Quick Start -->
    <div class="full-bleed pr-8" style="background: #FEFCF4;">
        <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl pt-1 pb-6">
            <h2>‚ö° TL;DR ‚Äî Quick Start</h2>
            <h3 class="pl-4">Try YINI in three quick steps:</h3>

            <ul class="space-y-6">
                <li>
                    <h3>1) Create a file</h3>
                    Save the two lines below as <code>config.yini</code>:<br />
                    <pre><code class="language-yini">{`^ App
name = 'Hello'`}</code></pre>
                    <p>
                        <span role="img" aria-label="warning">‚ö†Ô∏è</span>
                        Make sure you save the file with the <code>.yini</code> extension
                        (not <code>.txt</code>).
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <h3>2) Run this in your terminal</h3>
                    <p>From the same folder where you saved the file:</p>
                    <pre><code class="language-bash">npx yini-cli parse config.yini</code></pre>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <h3>3) See the result</h3>
                    <p>This prints the following JavaScript object:</p>
                    <pre><code class="language-yini">{`{ App: { name: 'Hello' } }`}</code></pre>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <h3>Bonus: Pretty-printed JSON output</h3>
                    <p>
                        Use the <code>--pretty</code> flag, and run this line:
                    </p>
                    <pre><code class="language-bash">npx yini-cli parse config.yini --pretty</code></pre>
                    <p>Which gives the following (JSON):</p>
                    <pre><code class="language-json">{`{
    "App": {
        "name": "Hello"
    }
}
`}</code></pre>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>
    </div>

    <section class="pb-6">
        <h2>üìù Example</h2>
        <h3>YINI code:</h3>
        <pre><code class="language-yini">{`^ App
  name = "My App"
  version = "1.2.3"
  pageSize = 25
  darkTheme = off
`}</code></pre>

        <h3>Parsed output (JS):</h3>
        <pre><code class="language-js">{`{
    "App": {
        "name": "My App",
        "version": "1.2.3",
        "pageSize": 25,
        "darkTheme": false
    }
}`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <div class="full-bleed pr-8" style="background: #F0FAFB;">
        <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl pt-1 pb-6">
            <h2>üß© Features</h2>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <strong>Readable & Familiar</strong>
                    <p class="mt-2">
                        Plain key/value with clear sections and optional strict
                        mode.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Structured</strong>
                    <p class="mt-2">
                        Native lists, objects, and nesting ‚Äî no guessing, no
                        surprises.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Specified</strong>
                    <p class="mt-2">
                        A formal, versioned spec and ANTLR grammar keep
                        implementations aligned.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Tooling First</strong>
                    <p class="mt-2">
                        Parsers, CLI, editors, and validation designed from day
                        one.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Open-source Software</strong>
                    <p class="mt-2">YINI is free, open-source software</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </section>
    </div>

    <p class="mt-3 text-base text-gray-600 md:text-base">
        <h2>‚ÑπÔ∏è About</h2>
        <p>
            YINI is a new configuration format, <strong
                >formalized in 2025</strong
            >. It's a structured configuration format designed for clarity, easy
            nesting, and strict validation.
        </p>
        <p>
            The format's syntax and behavior are defined in the
            <strong>YINI Specification</strong>, currently at
            <strong>Version 1.0 ‚Äî Candidate Release</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
            YINI was created and is maintained by Marko K. Sepp√§nen as an
            open-source project under the <a
                href="https://github.com/YINI-lang"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                class="text-slate-400 no-underline hover:text-sky-300 hover:underline"
                >YINI-lang organization</a
            >.
            <p>
                The specification, tooling, and ecosystem are actively evolving
                toward the first stable release.
            </p>
        </p>
    </p>

    <section>
        <h2>üõ†Ô∏è Contribute & Get Involved</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-700">
            YINI is open-source and evolving. You can help by trying it,
            reporting issues, contributing code, or just ‚≠ê the project on
            GitHub.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
            <a
                href={CONFIG.urls.external.gitHub.yiniOrg}
                target="_blank"
                rel="noreferrer"
                class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg border px-4 py-2"
                >GitHub Org ‚Üó</a
            >
            <a
                href={CONFIG.urls.hero.spec}
                class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg border px-4 py-2"
                >Read the Spec</a
            >
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>üî≠ Next steps</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <a href="/get-started">Get Started</a><br />
                <p class="mt-2">Learn how to install and use YINI from CLI.</p>
            </li>
            <!--li>
            <a href="/yini-playground">Try it Online</a><br />
            <p class="mt-2">Try it in the Playground.</p>
        </li-->
            <li>
                <a href="/yini-tutorial">Quick Tutorial</a><br />
                <p class="mt-2">
                    5-minute guided walkthrough of YINI ‚Äî the basics of the YINI
                    format and how to validate it.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="/yini-faq">FAQ</a><br />
                <p class="mt-2">Common questions answered.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="/specification">Specification</a><br />
                <p class="mt-2">
                    Official YINI format rules ‚Äî Full technical details of the
                    YINI format.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</BaseLayout>
